## âœ… **Step 1 â€“ Install & Check Services**

### **ðŸ“Œ On Both Machines**

```bash
# Install
sudo apt update && sudo apt install openssh-server apache2 iptables -y

# Test SSH
ssh shuhari@127.0.0.1       # Local SSH
ssh shuhari@192.168.80.130  # Debian1 âžœ Debian2
ssh shuhari@192.168.80.128  # Debian2 âžœ Debian1

# Test Apache2
links http://127.0.0.1       # Local site
links http://192.168.80.130  # Debian1 âžœ Debian2 site
links http://192.168.80.128  # Debian2 âžœ Debian1 site
```

---

## âœ… **Step 2 â€“ Basic Firewall Setup (Debian-01)**

```bash
# Confirm iptables installed
sudo which iptables

# View rules
sudo iptables -L -v

# Set default policy to DROP (forward)
sudo iptables -P FORWARD DROP

# Set INPUT to DROP
sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP

# If you drop INPUT, you may lock out SSH! So:
# Allow loopback first (always allow localhost)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT

# Allow ESTABLISHED connections
sudo iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

# âœ… Test self-SSH should work
ssh shuhari@127.0.0.1

# âœ… Test outbound SSH to other machine should work
ssh shuhari@192.168.80.130
```

---

## âœ… **Step 3 â€“ Allow SSH Only From Base Machine**

**Base machine IP:** `192.168.80.1`
**Allow SSH port 22 only from this IP**

```bash
# Allow SSH from base machine only
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.80.1 -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
```

**â— Now SSH from other IPs will fail except the allowed one.**

---

## âœ… **Step 4 â€“ Allow Specific Ports**

```bash
# Allow HTTP if needed (optional)
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
```

---

## âœ… **Step 5 â€“ Check & Save**

```bash
# View all rules with line numbers
sudo iptables -L --line-numbers -v
```

---

## âœ… **Step 6 â€“ Optional: Automate with Script**

```bash
cat > fw.sh <<EOF
#!/bin/bash
iptables -F
iptables -P FORWARD DROP
iptables -P INPUT DROP
iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.80.1 -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 80 -j ACCEPT
iptables -L -v
EOF

# Make executable
chmod 755 fw.sh

# Run
sudo ./fw.sh
```

---

## âœ… **Optional Maintenance**

| Command                      | Purpose                        |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| `iptables -L --line-numbers` | View rules with line numbers   |
| `iptables -D INPUT <num>`    | Delete rule number `<num>`     |
| `iptables -F`                | Flush all rules (be cautious!) |

---

# ðŸ”’ **iptables Practical â€” Make Rules Persistent After Reboot**

## âœ… **Step 1 â€” Save Rules Manually**

```bash
# Create a dedicated folder for storing iptables rules
sudo mkdir -p /etc/iptables

# Save current rules and write to file
sudo sh -c "iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4"

# Verify the file
ls -l /etc/iptables/
```

---

## âœ… **Step 2 â€” Install `iptables-persistent`**

```bash
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install iptables-persistent
```

ðŸ”¹ **When prompted:**
âœ” Save existing rules â†’ YES
âœ” Save IPv6 rules â†’ YES (or NO if not used)

---

## âœ… **Step 3 â€” Test**

```bash
# Reboot the system
sudo reboot

# After reboot, check the rules are restored
sudo iptables -L -v
```

---

## âœ… **Step 4 â€” Update Rules Later**

If you **modify** your firewall script and run it:

```bash
# Check current rules
sudo iptables -L

# Save the new rules again
sudo sh -c "iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4"
```

---

## âœ… **How `iptables-persistent` Works**

- It loads `/etc/iptables/rules.v4` (and rules.v6 for IPv6) automatically at boot.
- Any changes must be **saved** again to `rules.v4`.

